monsters.title: Cow
monsters.extract: Cows are common low level monsters new players train on. They are one of the first NPCs new players see in Lumbridge. Cows can help new players earn money, Cooking experience, and combat experience. The cowhides that they drop can be tanned to make leather or hard leather, or they can be sold for coins to players wanting to raise their Crafting level. While most locations containing cows are crowded, there are some spots usually vacant, like the spot north of the windmill north-west of Lumbridge. Along with cows, you can also find cow calves and dairy cows. Regular cows cannot be milked; attempting to do so using a bucket will display the message Only dairy cows are suitable for milking..

monsters.title: Goblin
monsters.extract:
Goblins are one of the most common, low-level monsters found around Gielinor. They are popularly killed by low-level players training their combat skills.
Goblins are often one of the first monsters a player will encounter, as they inhabit much of the area around Lumbridge.
The single armed goblin with a blue mail (as indicated in the gallery below) is the only aggressive goblin found anywhere, other than the variants found in the God Wars Dungeons. Whenever a player is standing anywhere inside the Goblin Cave (even when outside the goblin's direct surroundings), it will yell Halt intruder!, within regular time intervals. This goblin has a wander range spanning almost the entire goblin cave, so it may attack players practically anywhere inside these caves. Other than this single goblin, any other goblin can become aggressive upon searching any of the stacked boxes in the cave, with one random nearby goblin being selected to become aggressive every time the boxes are searched.

monsters.title: Hill Giant
monsters.extract:
A Hill Giant is a type of giant found in several locations around RuneScape. For free-to-play, the Edgeville Dungeon offers the most spawns, while for members, the Shayzien Giant Pit also has numerous spawns. The Edgeville dungeon may be accessed through the entrance located in the house north-east of Barbarian Village and west of the Cooks' Guild if the player has a Brass key. The Edgeville Dungeon area is usually very crowded in free-to-play worlds, as players like to gather Big bones to bury them for Prayer experience. Another free-to-play hill giants area was added at the Giants' Plateau, near Al Kharid (located east of the Al Kharid General Store and Louie's Armoured Legs Bazaar., east past the gap in the gate).
There will be fewer players fighting Hill Giants in Members worlds due to the better money making options for members, resulting in less crowds. There are two Hill Giants present in level 17-18 Wilderness; however, very few people go there because of the dangerous player killers in the area and its far distance from any bank. The closest bank for most Hill Giants in the Wilderness is in Edgeville. They are aggressive to players below combat level 57.
Hill giants have relatively low Defence for their level, which makes them quite good for experience from level 30 to level 50. Killing them in the Catacombs of Kourend is also one of the fastest ways to farm for Ancient shards and Dark totem pieces because of their low Hitpoints, allowing high level players to kill upwards of a couple hundred an hour.
The Hill Giant is one of the creatures that could potentially drop a Champion's scroll, making it a desirable monster both to train on for experience, due to its relatively high Hitpoints but low Defence, and a chance at its rare scroll drop. It can also drop the giant key, which is required to fight the hill giant boss Obor's lair for the first time, and loot his chest thereafter.
The giants found on the Giants' Plateau share the same drops as all other hill giants, except that they drop steel scimitars instead of steel longswords, and drop iron med helms instead of iron full helms.

monsters.title: Zombie
monsters.extract:
Zombies are generic monsters found throughout Gielinor, often located in cemeteries, sewers, and dungeons. They count as undead NPCs and are weak to the effects of both the Salve amulet and the Crumble Undead spell.
Most common zombies are low-leveled, hence serving as a decent training method for low-level players. Many locations have distinct zombie variants that have different combat levels, drops, and appearances.

monsters.title: Skeleton
monsters.extract: Skeletons are undead monsters found in various locations across Gielinor, often in graveyards and dungeons. Being an undead monster, they are susceptible to Crumble Undead and the Salve amulet. They are also often weak against crush attacks.

monsters.title: Giant rat
monsters.extract:
Giant rats are common, low-levelled monsters. They can often be found in swamps and sewers, and are sometimes killed by low-levelled players training their Combat skills as they are weak and can be easily found around Lumbridge and Varrock.
They are the first monster a player will defeat in Old School RuneScape, as Vannaka will task them with defeating one on Tutorial Island.
One of two giant rats found near Damis during Desert Treasure I can be used to safespot him by luring Damis and the other aggressive monsters behind it, making the fight considerably easier.

monsters.title: Spider
monsters.extract:
Spiders are found all over Gielinor, but most notably in the Stronghold of Security, where a stronger variant can be found in large numbers. Spiders are usually considered a nuisance and rarely drop items, and are generally only killed to quickly complete a spider slayer task.  
Similar to rats, spiders do not appear on the minimap.

monsters.title: Chicken
monsters.extract:
Chickens are a type of domesticated bird kept as livestock by farmers, and are often found inside pens in the farms of Gielinor.
Chickens are one of the weakest enemies in RuneScape, and are often killed by low-level players training their combat skills as they have very low defence and cannot deal damage to players: the chicken farms in Lumbridge are often crowded for this reason. Chickens will sometimes try to retreat when they have 1 hitpoint left.
Chickens count for bird Slayer tasks, which can be given by Turael.
Chickens are a source of several useful items, as when they are killed they drop raw chickens for Cooking, bones for Prayer, and 5 or 15 feathers for Fishing or Fletching. Feathers are usually in high demand, therefore killing chickens and selling their feathers can be somewhat profitable for low level players.
In most populated worlds, chicken coops are often full of bones, feathers, and raw chicken left by players training on the chickens. If one chooses to bury the bones and cook the chicken, they will be able to gain a small amount of Prayer and Cooking experience for free.
A variant type of chicken is attacked on Tutorial Island during the Magic tutorial.

monsters.title: Fire giant
monsters.extract:
Fire giants are powerful giants that are popular for training Ranged and Slayer. They are also the strongest of the standard giants, being significantly stronger than their Ice, Moss, and Hill giant relatives.
Fire giants are assigned by a multitude of Slayer Masters, providing fairly decent experience for both combat and Slayer. They're also frequently killed by Ironman players early on due to their signature rune scimitar drop, as they are fairly easy to access with numerous safespots. Low-level players may find enchanted pearl bolts helpful when training Ranged against these enemies. Although there are many locations where cannons can be used, none of these locations are in a multicombat area.

monsters.title: Moss giant
monsters.extract:
Moss giants are large giants, found in areas that are tied to nature. 
Moss giants are very commonly trained on, since their Defence level is rather low in comparison to other monsters of the same combat level, and they are vulnerable to Fire spells.
They can drop the mossy key, which is required to access the moss giant boss Bryophyta's lair for the first time, and loot her chest thereafter.
Stronger level 84 Moss Giants can be found in the Iorwerth Dungeon.

monsters.title: Ice giant
monsters.extract:
Ice giants are tall, light blue giants that appear at certain icy areas of the game. They are the second strongest giant type out of the standard giants, weaker than Fire giants, but stronger than Moss and Hill giants.
Ice giants are assigned only by Vannaka and Krystilia, although they aren't often killed by players outside of Wilderness slayer due to their poor loot compared to the weaker moss giants and hill giants. Ice giants have separate variants where they appear to be holding different weapons; a longsword, a warhammer, or a macuahuitl.

monsters.title: Giant spider
monsters.extract: Giant spiders are very large spiders most commonly seen around Lumbridge.

monsters.title: Minotaur
monsters.extract:
Minotaur are found on level one of the Stronghold of Security. They drop the right skull half, one of four parts of the Skull sceptre. These monsters are great for training due to their low defence, but have high attack damage making them dangerous for un-equipped players.
Minotaurs are a common method of Ranged training as they can be safespotted and commonly drop iron arrows.

monsters.title: Ogre
monsters.extract:
Ogres are a monster found throughout Gielinor, most notably the ogre city of Gu'Tanoth. 
The best place to kill ogres for Slayer is directly west of Yanille, near where Og is situated and the small island, although the location may be crowded with cannon users that can make training there inhospitable; if that's the case, it is possible to kill the ogres camping in the ruins immediately to the north, behind a line of trees, as those are not affected by the cannon.
Alternatively, if the player has level 46 Thieving, they can access the Chaos Druid Tower that has 7 ogres in its dungeon, where it is usually quiet. After completion of Biohazard, caged ogres found in the Combat Training Camp can also be fought using ranged and magic; melee in the training camp is possible if using a halberd to attack the ogres through the caging. These ogres are unaggressive.
